{{quotation|Last year Mr. Welles went to work for Lockheed — building airplanes by acting, producing and a directing a [[Ceiling Unlimited|radio show]]. With this stint of vocal welding and literate riveting behind him he was ripe for a magic show of his own, to be full of sound and fury, corn and canaries. The night of Aug. 3 saw that show light up the Los Angeles [[Blackout (wartime)|dimout]].|''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', August 29, 1943<ref>Berch, Barbara, [https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9E0CE5D6173EE03BBC4151DFBE668388659EDE "Orson the Great"]. ''[[The New York Times Magazine]]'', August 29, 1943, page 11.</ref>}}

''The Mercury Wonder Show'' ran August 3–September 9, 1943, in an 80-by-120-foot tent<ref name="Billboard">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lgwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT3&lpg=PT3&dq=Mercury+Wonder+Show+tent&source=bl&ots=XzgizTvzqY&sig=9uruv7-Ne2_fQxdSKEo7rSCLRJU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VzaXU4vmDsKQyASmooKIDQ&ved=0CF8Q6AEwCTgK#v=onepage&q=Mercury%20Wonder%20Show%20tent&f=false |title=Welles Dishes Magic, Sawdust at Mercury Bow |publisher=Abbott, Sam, ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', August 14, 1943, page 4 |accessdate=2014-06-10}}</ref> located at 9000 [[Cahuenga Boulevard]], in the heart of [[Hollywood]].<ref name="Genii">Wheldon, Wynn Pierce, "Orson Welles the Magician". ''[[Genii (magazine)|Genii, The Conjurors' Magazine]]'', Volume 63 Number 2, February 15, 2000</ref>{{Rp|26|date=June 2014}}<ref name="TIOW"/>{{Rp|377|date=June 2014}} The brand-new, two-pole Big Top offered 1,100 bleacher seats — all of them free — to service members. In the center were 400 folding chairs for the public, with tickets priced at $1.65 to $5.50 for adults and 55 cents for children. For opening night only, the public seats were $5.50 and $11.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|170|date=June 2014}} Charity-minded Hollywood celebrities could pay $30 (the equivalent of ${{formatnum:{{inflation|US|30|1943}}}} today) for one of the 25 to 30 seats in the sucker section;<ref name="TIOW"/>{{Rp|177|date=June 2014}} it cost $50 or $100 for one of the two super-sucker seats nailed down directly behind the massive tent poles.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|171|date=June 2014}} Welles recalled subjecting this highest-paying public — "usually [[Samuel Goldwyn|Sam Goldwyn]] or [[Jack L. Warner|Jack Warner]] or somebody like that" — to humiliations that included having eggs broken over their heads. "And they had to pretend it was all good fun, because our boys in khaki were there, you know. We really gave it to them."<ref name="TIOW"/>{{Rp|177|date=June 2014}}

After performing in the official premiere August 3,<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|171, 177}} Rita Hayworth was thereafter forbidden to appear in ''The Mercury Wonder Show'' by [[Columbia Pictures|Columbia]] boss [[Harry Cohn]]. When her lawyer confirmed that Hayworth could indeed be sued for breach of contract — filming was then under way for ''[[Cover Girl (1944 film)|Cover Girl]]'' — Welles persuaded her not to jeopardize her entire career by going on anyway, as she vowed to do.<ref name="Leaming Hayworth"/>{{Rp|88}} He phoned his friend [[Marlene Dietrich]] and asked her to fill in. "Come teach me the tricks and I do it," Dietrich replied.<ref name="Leaming Hayworth"/>{{Rp|89}} "She was the good soldier of all time," Welles said.<ref name="Leaming OW">{{cite book |last=Leaming |first=Barbara |title=Orson Welles, A Biography |publisher=[[Viking Press]] |location=New York |date=1985 |isbn=978-0-618-15446-3}}</ref>{{Rp|268}}

At intermission September 7, 1943, [[KMPC#KMPC-710|KMPC]] radio interviewed audience and cast members of ''The Mercury Wonder Show'' — including Welles and Hayworth, who were married earlier that day. Welles remarked that ''The Mercury Wonder Show'' had been performed for approximately 48,000 members of the U.S. armed forces.<ref name="TIOW"/>{{Rp|378|date=June 2014}}<ref name="Bret Wood">[[Bret Wood|Wood, Bret]], ''Orson Welles: A Bio-Bibliography''. Westport, Connecticut: Greenwood Press, 1990 {{ISBN|0-313-26538-0}}</ref>{{Rp|129|date=June 2014}}

Looking back on the experience 30 years later, Welles said the show was primarily made "for fun", but that "it's one of our great works" and that the Mercury Theatre were "as proud of that as anything we ever did."<ref name="TIOW">[[Orson Welles|Welles, Orson]], and [[Peter Bogdanovich]], edited by [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]], ''[[This is Orson Welles]]''. New York: [[HarperCollins]] Publishers 1992 {{ISBN|0-06-016616-9}}.</ref>{{Rp|177|date=January 2014}}

A reduced version toured army bases around the U.S. Several episodes of the 1944 [[CBS Radio]] show ''[[The Orson Welles Almanac]]'' that were performed live before audiences of servicemen were also called the Mercury Wonder Show.<ref name="Almanac Part 1">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/1944OrsonWellesRadioAlmanacpart1 |title=Orson Welles Almanac—Part 1 |publisher=[[Internet Archive]] |accessdate=2014-02-09}}</ref><ref name="Almanac Part 2">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/1944OrsonWellesRadioAlmanacpart2 |title=Orson Welles Almanac—Part 2 |publisher=[[Internet Archive]] |accessdate=2014-02-10}}</ref>

==Cultural references==

==="The Trunk Murder"===
Welles wrote, directed and performed in a plug for ''The Mercury Wonder Show'' that ran in ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' magazine November 16, 1943. In "The Trunk Murder", the magician solves the double murder of Joseph Cotten and showgirl assistant Eleanor Counts. George (Shorty) Chirello, Death Valley Mack, Merry Hamilton and Tommy Hanlon Jr. appear in the five-photo crime puzzle. "Don't be embarrassed if you can't work it," readers are advised, "since [Welles] admits he has never yet solved a LOOK ''Photocrime''."<ref name="Look">{{cite journal |last=Welles |first=Orson |authorlink=Orson Welles |date=November 16, 1943 |title=The Trunk Murder: Orson the Great summons up corpses  |journal=[[Look (American magazine)|Look]] |publisher= |volume=7 |issue=23 |pages=56, 58–59, 68  }}</ref><ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|637}}

===''Follow the Boys''===
[[File:FollowPoster01.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Poster for ''[[Follow the Boys]]'' (1944)]]
A portion of the stage show was filmed and included in the 1944 variety film, ''[[Follow the Boys]]''. The film segment was directed by Welles, uncredited.

Welles and Dietrich agreed to appear in the film while ''The Mercury Wonder Show'' was still running. The seven-minute segment was shot on the Universal lot in late September 1943. Welles traded his robe and fez for white tie and tails, and brought along a crew from the show — Shorty Chirello, Tommy Hanlon, Professor Bill and his Circus Symphony, Death Valley Mack, two female assistants and eight chorus girls. Welles performed a few illusions; his own appearance on stage and the comic version of the sawing-a-woman-in-half illusion featuring Dietrich were achieved with trick photography.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|184}} Welles received $30,000 for his part in the film. The segment was to be shot in four or five days, but Welles stretched filming to 16 days to give additional pay to his crew.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|185–186}}

===Memorabilia===
A framed copy of the playbill for ''The Mercury Wonder Show'' was sold at auction October 31, 2002, for $1,610.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://catalogue.swanngalleries.com/asp/fullCatalogue.asp?salelot=1949+++++241+&refno=++515382&saletype= |title=The Mercury Wonder Show for Service Men. Orson the Magnificent.  (Lot 241) |publisher=Magic—The Manny Weltman Houdini Collection (Sale 1949), [[Swann Galleries]] |accessdate=2014-06-09}}</ref> In an auction April 26, 2014, the advertising herald was sold for $1,062.50;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.ha.com/c/item.zx?saleNo=7089&lotNo=46018 |title=An Orson Welles Herald from The Mercury Wonder Show, 1943 (Lot 46018) |publisher=Entertainment & Music Memorabilia Signature Auction, New York (#7089), Heritage Auctions |accessdate=2014-05-11}}</ref> the item was among those found in boxes and trunks of Welles's personal possessions by his daughter Beatrice Welles.<ref>{{cite news | title=Orson Welles' camera, other items up for auction | url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/orson-welles-camera-among-70-items-auction |work=[[Associated Press]] | date=March 31, 2014 | last=Tang | first=Terry |  accessdate=2014-05-11}}</ref>

A scrapbook kept by George (Shorty) Chirello was offered as part of the "TCM Presents … There's No Place Like Hollywood" auction November 24, 2014, at [[Bonhams]] in New York. Chirello worked for Welles from about 1942 to 1952; his scrapbook begins in August 1943 with clippings about ''The Mercury Wonder Show'', and includes a copy of the playbill. Chirello managed props for the show,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://images1.bonhams.com/original?src=Images/live/2014-10/29/S-22196-0-1.pdf |title=TCM Presents … There's No Place Like Hollywood  |publisher=[[Bonhams]], sale 22196, lot 278, catalog for auction November 24, 2014 |accessdate=2014-11-01}}</ref> and acted as Welles's comedy assistant on stage and in the film ''Follow the Boys''.<ref name="Whaley"/>{{Rp|165, 184}} The scrapbook and a directors chair inscribed "Orson Welles" were sold as a single lot and brought $13,750 at auction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bonhams.com/auctions/22196/ |title=Print Results, TCM Presents … There's No Place Like Hollywood  |publisher=[[Bonhams]], sale 22196, lot 278, November 24, 2014 |accessdate=2014-11-25}}</ref>

